[Scene 1 | 0–4s]
"Every early neural network used sigmoid — so why did it completely KILL deep networks above 3 layers? Watch this."

[Scene 2 | 4–9s]
"Sigmoid squashes any number into the range 0 to 1. Formula: sigma-of-x equals 1 over 1 plus e-to-the-negative-x. Smooth. Bounded. Looks perfect."

[Scene 3 | 9–15s]
"But look at its derivative — the gradient signal. It peaks at just 0.25... and collapses to nearly ZERO at the extremes."

[Scene 4 | 15–20s]
"During backpropagation, gradients multiply across layers. 0.25 times 0.25 times 0.25 — you get 0.016. One more layer? Just 0.004. It vanishes."

[Scene 5 | 20–26s]
"By the time you reach the early layers, the gradient is essentially 0.004. Those layers receive NO useful signal — they stop learning completely."

[Scene 6 | 26–32s]
"But sigmoid IS still valuable — at the output layer of a binary classifier, it converts any raw score into a clean probability between 0 and 1."

[Scene 7 | 32–37s]
"So: use sigmoid ONLY at the output layer for binary classification. In hidden layers of deep networks — NEVER. Use ReLU instead."

